history and has created sharply divided opinions on the extent to which law may be said to be a product of the society that created it. This work is a balanced assessment of the different points of view battling against each other in this ongoing argument. It contains an introductory chapter by Alan Watson, whose views on the relationship between law and society have caused some controversy. In the following chapters, a distinguished group of international scholars get stuck in to the debate by focusing on studies of law and empire, codes and codification, death and economics, commerce and procedure. By looking at these specific areas, Beyond Dogmatics contributes to the larger debate about Roman private law in Roman society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aLawxSocial aspectsxRomexRome (Empire). 0aLawxSocial aspectszRome. 0aRoman law. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 4aLaw. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aAubert, J-J, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCairns, J. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarries, J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, A. D. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMetzger, E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, E. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlessis, P. J. Du, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRees, R. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobinson, O. F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTuori, K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatson, A., ec